# Feature flag tooling (awaits ADR-10)

## Rule
Until ADR-10 resolves, feature flags use a single convention per repo:

- Env var `FEATURE_<UPPER_SNAKE>` with values `on` / `off`, checked at process start.
- For per-tenant rollouts, a `feature_flags` collection on the owning service's DB (one row per tenant × feature).

No ad hoc `if (user.email.endsWith("@freightify.com"))` style gates.

## Why
No feature-flag tooling is documented today. Tenant rollout is needed; a repeatable convention prevents each service from inventing its own storage pattern.

## Constraints
- Flag definitions live in a per-service `flags.go` / `flags.ts` / `flags.py` with: name, default value, description, owning ticket, planned removal date.
- A flag is temporary by default; a TTL in the flag definition forces a cleanup decision.
- Flag reads happen at the service layer, not in handlers or controllers directly.
- When ADR-10 accepts a tool (LaunchDarkly / Unleash / homegrown), existing flags migrate; the rule is swept.

## Examples

### Good
```go
// flags.go
const FeatureFRLCCategory = Flag{Name: "FRLC_CATEGORY", Default: false, Owner: "EFP-1234", RemoveBy: "2026-10-01"}

if flag.On(ctx, flags.FeatureFRLCCategory) { ... }
```

### Bad
```go
if os.Getenv("EXPERIMENT") == "true" { ... }  // ad hoc, undocumented
```

